tip.text: Loved the corn & beetroot fritters with avo, egg & eggplant kasundi (oh yum). Add the trout, perfect. Fritters were a bit doughy but no biggie. Space is small, fine if you don't mind sharing tables.
Lovely and simple home made pasta; rich & flavourful. I'm not one for pasta outside but the octopus pasta in eggplant sauce was worth it.
Having been here a 2nd time & trying the sushi proper, I have to rescind my previous tip. Sushi = excellent. One of the best I've had in London.
The fried curd cheese was good, as was the tenderloin (I was in mushroom sauce heaven). My server was really sweet too, would definitely love to come back!
Pork cheek ragout with pasta is perfect for a rainy day. Pickled herring not bad too but marinated salmon was drowning in fennel & pear. Cosy place though, quiet if you come early.
Not impressed by food or service. Though the seafood pasta was good, serving frozen, synthetic fish with fresh prawns & mussels is not acceptable.
Taramasalata wasn't too bad but the grilled octopus stole the show. It was delicious; soft, simple marinade of herbs and olive oil. Though I took my time with it, I didn't harden or become too chewy.
Cute little coffee joint tucked away in Ealing. Perfect for a chilled out Sunday. Food is really good too (venison sausage sandwich, yum!). Staff really pleasant too.
A little pricey, but not bad for a good vegan meal. The croquettes, bangers & mash and burger are pretty good. I'd recommend the starter mezze to try a little bit of everything.
Good sushi for a local place. Lunch deals are worth it, rolls are tasty & sashimi is really fresh! I'd recommend the chazuke on a cold night. So comforting. 🍲
Decent dosai but they were a little scant with the onions for the Rava onion one. The spicy red chutney was the best IMHO. Fresh sweet paan FTW.

One of the best paella I've had in the Catalan region. Rice was flavorful & seafood was fresh. Homemade tomato oil & garlic aioli delicious with bread. Service a little slow but my server was so sweet
Service staff seemed lost at times. Food was just ok; found the xiao long bao skin a little too thick & roast meats nothing to rave about. Also note that they charge £1 for chopped red chili in sauce
Nice place to chill, cocktails are interesting enough albeit a little weak. I liked their se of fresh ingredients. Service is slow & a friend remarked that it was a too brightly lit for a bar.

contact.facebookName: Mars Bar by Mixes from Mars

venue.name: Mars Bar By Mixes From Mars (Closed)

tip.text: The set for 2 wasn't worth it IMHO. The dishes were a hit & miss. While the scallop, lobster & barramundi were very good, the clams were not fresh & razor clams were average. Great setting though.
Excellent breakfast, good portions. Toastie was chock full of cheese & ham. Grilled mushrooms perfectly done as was the mackerel; they smoke it in-house. Coffee apparently decent too. Two thumbs up!
Good pizzas at reasonable prices. Choose you own sauce, cheese & toppings with the DIY option; fun with interesting options like blue crab & roasted squash but nothing special.
Awesome kimchi soup & pancake. The grilled saba fish was worth it; huge, meaty slab that was so tender. The bancha was disappointing (sausage in ketchup, really?) but the main dishes made up for it.
These guys know their stuff. The food is good, no doubt. Not as good as some of the other restaurants in the area but you won't be disappointed. I recommend the Mini Spanish Breakfast & paella.
Huge menu! I think the best bet is to order lots to share. The grilled items seem to be the better choice as my sashimi rice bowl wasn't very impressive. Will definitely try more of them next time.

Just sit back, let the chef do his magic & be prepared to have probably some of the best Japanese food in Singapore. Atmosphere is a little stern but adds to the dining experience. Service impeccable.

Given the price I expected a lot. I got average food with no finesse in execution & inconsistent service (owing to a clueless waiter). Liked the decor. Too bad it did nothing to enhance my experience.
The tuna tataki was good & staff friendly. They held my reservation for longer than they'd said they would. The bread varies; the wholemeal was soft but sourdough was too heavy & a bit stale.
A cool spot to chill at any afternoon. Really like the deco too; not too tacky and overdone. Non-coffee drinkers, try the chai tea latte. Light with just the right amount of spice.
Quirky layout, friendly staff, tasty desserts. Recommend the Nutella pie and honey-cinnamon ice cream. Root beer cake was interesting. The rum & raisin and vanilla ice creams were too watered down.
Breakfast is quite good, portions are big for reasonable prices. Great to chill out with a glass of iced calamansi juice on a hot day.

location.address: 965A Upp Changi Road North, Changi Garden
formattedAddress: 965A Upp Changi Road North, Changi Garden (btwn Mariam Way & Jln Mariam)

tip.text: The decor is too haphazard. And  some decent chairs would be much appreciated; tall people just cannot sit on milk crates. Crostini's alright for a snack, though I did find it a tad bland.
Come on an empty stomach & try the 7 or 9 course meals. Some dishes were outstanding, most notably the sashimi, foie gras chawanmushi & grilled swordfish; others were just OK.
